<p>&#61482;&#61489;&#61493;&#61488;&#61494;&#61492;&#61496;&#61495;&#61482;&#61472;
</p>
<p><b>Human Rights Council 
Twenty-eighth session 
</b></p>
<p>Agenda item 10 
</p>
<p><b>Technical assistance and capacity-building 
</b></p>
<p><b>  France, Haiti: Statement by the President</b>&#61482;<b> 
</b></p>
<p><b>  </b>28/&#8230;<b> Situation of human rights in Haiti 
</b></p>
<p> At the twenty-fifth session of the Human Rights Council, held from 2 to 27 March 
</p>
<p>2015, during consideration of agenda item 10, entitled &#8220;Technical assistance and capacity-
</p>
<p>building&#8221;, the President of the Council made the following statement: 
</p>
<p> 1. The Human Rights Council thanks the Independent Expert for his report on 
</p>
<p>the human rights situation in Haiti and takes note of the latest legal and political 
</p>
<p>developments in Haiti, which have been marked in particular by progress in civil, political, 
</p>
<p>economic, social and cultural rights:1 
</p>
<p> (<i>a</i>) The implementation, in May 2014, of Phase II of the legal aid bureaux with a 
</p>
<p>view to making justice accessible to the poorest; 
</p>
<p> (<i>b</i>) The enactment, in 2014, of the law on preventing and combating corruption 
</p>
<p>and the law on maternity, paternity and filiation; 
</p>
<p> (<i>c</i>) The launch, on 23 February 2015, in Kenscoff, within the framework of the 
</p>
<p>three-year agricultural revival programme, of the &#8220;spring agricultural campaign&#8221; 
</p>
<p>programme aimed at increasing production and the availability of basic food commodities 
</p>
<p>for the benefit of the population; 
</p>
<p> (<i>d</i>) The announcement, on 5 March 2015, of the development of a new security 
</p>
<p>plan for the metropolitan region, in order to put an end to violence in the capital; 
</p>
<p> (<i>e</i>) The appointment of a new President of the Court of Cassation and the High 
</p>
<p>Council of the Judiciary, and his inauguration on 9 March 2015; 
</p>
<p> (<i>f</i>) The launch, on 11 March 2015, by the Government of Haiti, the United 
</p>
<p>Nations and their partners, of a transitional appeal for the 2015&#8211;2016 period in order to 
</p>
<p>reduce the extreme vulnerability of populations and build resilience in Haiti; 
</p>
<p>  
</p>
<p> &#61482; Non-member State of the Human Rights Council.  
 1 A/HRC/28/82. 
</p>
<p><b> 
</b>United Nations A/HRC/28/L.37 
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p><b>General Assembly </b>Distr.: Limited 
26 March 2015 
</p>
<p>English 
</p>
<p>Original: French </p>


<p><b>2</b> GE.15-06487 
</p>
<p> (<i>g</i>) The submission, on 13 March 2015, to the President of the Republic, of the 
</p>
<p>preliminary draft revision of the Criminal Code, by the members of the Presidential 
</p>
<p>Commission for the reform of justice established in January 2012; 
</p>
<p> (<i>h</i>) The continuation of the work of the Interministerial Human Rights 
</p>
<p>Committee, set up in May 2013, to coordinate and harmonize public human rights policies. 
</p>
<p> 2. The Council welcomes the renewed commitment of Haiti to the effective 
</p>
<p>implementation of international human rights conventions to which Haiti is a party, with 
</p>
<p>the submission, in October 2014, to the Human Rights Committee, of the initial report on 
</p>
<p>the implementation of the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights and the 
</p>
<p>forthcoming submission by Haiti to the treaty bodies concerned of its reports on the Rights 
</p>
<p>of the Child, in January 2016, on economic, social and cultural rights, in January 2016, and 
</p>
<p>on the elimination of all forms of discrimination against women, in February 2016; 
</p>
<p> 3. The Council also welcomes the reaffirmation of the commitment of the 
</p>
<p>Haitian authorities to improve the living conditions of Haitian women and men by, inter 
</p>
<p>alia, devoting greater attention to respect for human rights; 
</p>
<p> 4. The Council welcomes the inauguration, on 23 January 2015, of a new 
</p>
<p>Provisional Electoral Council, as well as the publication of the Electoral Ordinance and the 
</p>
<p>electoral calendar by the Provisional Electoral Council, and the official launch of the 
</p>
<p>electoral process on 13 March 2015. The Council calls on the Haitian authorities and all 
</p>
<p>parties concerned to respect the electoral calendar published in the Official Gazette and to 
</p>
<p>work for the satisfactory holding of elections;  
</p>
<p> 5. The Council encourages, in this context, the Government of Haiti to continue 
</p>
<p>strengthening the rule of law, through inter alia combating impunity, corruption, criminality 
</p>
<p>and its causes. The Council strongly encourages the Government of Haiti to continue to 
</p>
<p>strengthen the capacities of the national police and the judicial system, with a view to 
</p>
<p>ensuring the functioning of public institutions and services and the enjoyment of all human 
</p>
<p>rights;  
</p>
<p> 6. The Council also welcomes the launch, on 2 March 2015, of the &#8220;crackdown&#8221; 
</p>
<p>operation aimed at providing an urgent and structured response to the phenomenon of 
</p>
<p>prolonged pretrial detention, as well as the establishment of a &#8220;crackdown&#8221; Committee. The 
</p>
<p>Council calls on the Government of Haiti to strengthen its efforts to address the causes of 
</p>
<p>prolonged pretrial detention and to reduce its use;  
</p>
<p> 7. The Security Council encourages the Government of Haiti to strengthen the 
</p>
<p>national institutions for the protection of human rights, in particular the Office of Citizen 
</p>
<p>Protection, and to provide it with adequate resources;  
</p>
<p> 8. The Council strongly encourages the Government of Haiti to continue to 
</p>
<p>adopt the necessary political and legal measures to guarantee the rights of members of 
</p>
<p>vulnerable groups, including children in domestic employment;  
</p>
<p> 9. The Council also strongly encourages the Government of Haiti to strengthen 
</p>
<p>women&#8217;s participation in political life and to continue the fight against gender-based 
</p>
<p>violence and discrimination;  
</p>
<p> 10. The Council recognizes that the full enjoyment of human rights, including 
</p>
<p>civil and political as well as economic, social and cultural rights, constitutes a factor of 
</p>
<p>peace, stability and development in Haiti; 
</p>
<p> 11. The Council encourages the international community as a whole and, in 
</p>
<p>particular, international donors, the Group of Latin American and Caribbean States, the 
</p>
<p>group of countries known as the Friends of Haiti, specialized agencies of the United 
</p>
<p>Nations and, in particular, the Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human </p>


<p>GE.15-06487 <b>3 
</b></p>
<p>Rights, to strengthen their cooperation and coordination with the Haitian authorities with a 
</p>
<p>view to the full realization of all human rights in Haiti;  
</p>
<p> 12. The Council welcomes and approves the request of the Haitian authorities for 
</p>
<p>a one-year extension of the mandate of the Independent Expert on the situation of human 
</p>
<p>rights in Haiti, which is concerned with technical assistance and capacity-building;  
</p>
<p> 13. The Council encourages the Independent Expert to continue to work with 
</p>
<p>international institutions, donors and the international community in order to raise their 
</p>
<p>awareness of the need to provide their expertise and sufficient resources to support the 
</p>
<p>efforts made by the Haitian authorities to rebuild the country and pursue sustainable 
</p>
<p>development; 
</p>
<p> 14. The Council also encourages the Independent Expert to continue to work 
</p>
<p>with the Government of Haiti, the non-governmental organizations of Haiti and civil 
</p>
<p>society in Haiti. It invites the Government of Haiti to continue its active cooperation with 
</p>
<p>civil society; 
</p>
<p> 15. The Council invites the Independent Expert to assist the Haitian Government 
</p>
<p>in the implementation of his own recommendations and those made by the other special 
</p>
<p>procedures; 
</p>
<p> 16. The Council also invites the Independent Expert to submit his report on the 
</p>
<p>situation of human rights in Haiti to the Council at its thirty-first session. It further invites 
</p>
<p>him to undertake a mission to Haiti and to report on that mission to the Council at its thirty-
</p>
<p>first session. 
</p>
<p>    </p>

